targets should be individualized based on duration of
diabetes, age, comorbid conditions, and other
considerations.

of diabetes.
Currently, no consensus exists regarding use of
hemoglobin A1c for diagnosis of diabetes for children.

Desirable range <100 mg/dL for primary prevention;
<70 mg/dL for patients with CHD or diabetic patients
with > or = 2 CHD risk factors.
LDL-C is now calculated using the Martin-Hopkins
calculation, which is a validated novel method providing
better accuracy than the Friedewald equation in the
estimation of LDL-C.
Martin SS et al. JAMA. 2013;310(19): 2061-2068
(http://education.QuestDiagnostics.com/faq/FAQ164)
For patients with diabetes plus 1 major ASCVD risk
factor, treating to a non-HDL-C goal of <100 mg/dL
(LDL-C of <70 mg/dL) is considered a therapeutic
option.

tr.td: Scribed by Devendra Bisht under the supervision of Dr. Francesco Santoni-Rugiu

We reviewed and discussed her coronary stress testing with Lexiscan, which revealed a mild fixed defect in the apical region. Given her abnormal coronary stress test, we also reviewed her lipid panel from a prior visit, which showed an LDL of 92 and a hemoglobin A1c of 6.2%, with normal kidney function noted. We discussed initiating OMT including statin therapy, but she prefers to defer at this time and attempt lifestyle modification first. She was counseled on reducing her intake of fried and fatty foods, full-fat dairy, red meats, and egg yolks. Given her persistent epigastric burning and abdominal discomfort with history of GERD, she is requesting a referral for GI, we will refer her to Dr. Lance Siegel for further gastrointestinal evaluation and possible treatment adjustment, as her current regimen has not alleviated her symptoms. We also reviewed the data from her Kardia device, which showed no abnormalities and documented normal sinus rhythm. All questions and concerns were answered and addressed. A heart-healthy diet and a healthy lifestyle were encouraged and endorsed. She is to follow up in 6-8 weeks, or sooner should symptoms worsen. She agrees to the plan of care.
Scribed by Devendra Bisht and Daliah Rodriguez under the supervision of Dr. Rishi Bajaj

td.paragraph: For her lightheadedness, dizziness and
history of bradycardia, we will arrange for an EKG. We will obtain insurance
approval for echocardiogram. We will also arrange for further ischemic
evaluation with coronary stress testing. For her dizziness, we will arrange for
carotid doppler. For her cold feet, we will arrange for an ABI/PVR. EKG reviewed
and discussed revealing sinus bradycardia with a heart rate of 47. She is not
on any beta blocker therapy at this time and reports only taking omeprazole for
GERD and amitriptyline at times. Carotid doppler preliminary images were reviewed
and discussed revealing mild plaque and no significant stenosis. For her cold
feet, an ABI/PVR was completed which revealed an RLE 0.74 and an LLE 1.1. We
discussed evaluation with EP, Dr. Santoni, for her significant bradycardia. We
also discussed MCT monitor which we will complete at the next visit. She
reports recently having an event monitor completed but is unsure of the findings.
All questions and concerns were answered and addressed. Heart healthy diet and
healthy lifestyle encouraged and endorsed. We will see her back next week
alongside EP or sooner if symptoms arise. She agrees to the plan of care.
Time Spent:
Total time spent 89 minutes. More than 50% of the time spent in
face-to-face conversation, examination, discussing treatment options and
procedures, pathophysiology, and anatomy. Diet and lifestyle modifications were
discussed in great detail. Images were personally reviewed by me in front
of the patient and/or family member and explained on our graphic diagram.
Treatment options, risks, benefits and alternative treatments discussed
with the patient in detail. All questions and concerns answered. All
records were reviewed in detail

tr.td: Scribed by Shashank Kapoor under the supervision of Dr. Rishi Bajaj and Marion Hayes, NP

td.paragraph: For
further ischemic evaluation of her significant exertional shortness of breath
and sinus bradycardia, we arranged for coronary stress testing with Lexiscan
during today's visit. The risks, benefits, and alternatives were discussed in
great detail. She tolerated the Lexiscan well, and we will review and discuss
the results at her next visit. An echocardiogram was completed today to
evaluate her cardiavascular morphology in the setting of exertional dyspnea.
Preliminary images were reviewed and discussed, which revealed a preserved
ejection fraction. A bilateral lower extremity arterial doppler was also
completed today to further evaluate the numbness, tingling, cramping, and
fatigue she experiences in her lower extremities. Preliminary images revealed
mild atherosclerotic plaque. She was encouraged to remain compliant with a
structured home-based exercise regimen for symptom relief. All questions and
concerns were answered and addressed. A heart-healthy diet and healthy
lifestyle were encouraged and endorsed.She is to follow up in one week to
review her Lexiscan results, or sooner should symptoms worsen, progress, or if
new symptoms arise. She agrees to the plan of care.

tr.td: Scribed by Devendra Bisht and Phoebe Tarta under the supervision of Dr. Rishi Bajaj

We have reviewed and discussed the results of her recent coronary stress testing, which revealed mild apical fixed defects possibly secondary to breast attenuation. She is without any angina symptoms at this time. We will arrange for fasting routine labs today to evaluate her cholesterol panel. She had previous outside labs completed, which showed some hyperlipidemia. However, at the time of her last evaluation, her diet was not optimal. She is also trying to wean herself off Amitriptyline at this time. She states she has significant sciatica pain, which it controls. However, we discussed discontinuing her trialene for neuropathy pain, and we will consider initiation of Metanx at the next visit if she is off Amitriptyline. All questions and concerns were answered and addressed. A heart healthy diet and healthy lifestyle. We will see her back in 1-2 weeks for a review of labs or sooner if symptoms arise. She agrees to the plan of care.
Scribed by Sushil Rai under the supervision of Dr. Rishi Bajaj and Marion Hayes, NP

td.paragraph: Labs
were reviewed and discussed today revealing an A1C of 6.2, consistent
with prediabetes. CMP, CBC, lipid panel, hepatic function, thyroid
function, vitamin D, and apolipoprotein studies were all reviewed and
noted to be within or near normal limits. We counseled the patient on
the importance of a low-glycemic, heart-healthy diet, regular
exercise, and weight reduction to address prediabetes and prevent
progression to type 2 diabetes mellitus. She is scheduled to follow
up in the office on 07/29 for continued cardiovascular evaluation and
monitoring of metabolic parameters. She agrees with the proposed plan
of care.

Patient was informed of the telemedicine visit by our office staff. Telemedicine was described in detail to the patient as the use of synchronous video and audio communication to provide clinical care from a distance. A telemedicine visit can provide the same medical standard of care for specific conditions. The patient was informed that the practice staff located at the provider's office would assist in carrying out any recommendations and clinical care.
Patient Location: Home
Lack of strict HIPPA Rules. Patient expressed verbal interest in the telemedicine visit and granted consent to proceed.
